column168: Description Of Events

On May 3, 2022, Ward Trucking terminal personnel reported a 35-gallon release of Optimull, a hazardous, UN32666, Corrosive Liquid (Sodium Hydroxide), 8, PG III. According to terminal personnel, a 275-gallon poly tote was punctured by a forklift that resulted in the release to the trailer floor, dock floor, and the ground below. A team was dispatched to clean the release and containerize waste to be staged on site pending final disposition.
Shannon reports (2) (5-GALLON) plastic pails of Acetone were damaged, they are empty, material cleaned and put into an overpack. Damage occurred from a puncture from forklift operator.

column168: At 0705 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (XLF) about a cargo release.  It was reported that due to improper loading, approximately 1 quart of 944RT004-DO RED (Hazardous - UN1866) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the dock floor in OS&D. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct cleanup operations. At 1042 ET, EnviroServe arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1 quart of product released to a 1' x 1' area of the dock floor. The damaged drum was placed into a 110 gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted area and collected. All waste was placed into the overpack. The waste was then staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 1635 EST XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at the terminal. It was reported that approximately 1 pint of UN3267 Nalcon 60585 released impacting the dock floor. ERTS dispatched Cleaning Guys to conduct cleanup. At 1910 ET, Cleaning Guys personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5 gallons of product released to a 3' x 3' area of the dock floor due to a faulty gasket. The gasket was replaced and the tote was secured for shipment. Crew cleaned the impacted area with hydrochloric acid and absorbent pads. The waste was placed into a 55 gallon poly drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The damaged tote was cut up and then containerized along with all spent absorbents into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. The waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: SequenceEvent: Package had loose closures therefore it was brought to QA. DescribePack: Betco: advanced alcohol gel sanitizer had the caps come off therefore causing an internal leakage during transit. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was leaking therefore it was placed in a spillage bin to avoid any spillage on other packages.

SequenceEvent: Recovered from trailer on unload. Upon recovery, package was found loaded on top of and around other hazmat damages. Upon inspection, package was found loaded into the trailer upside down with heavy external deterioration and internal leakage. DescribePack: Package was found with a large amount of residue on each of the caps of the internal bottles. Given that it was loaded upside down, it was likely due in large part to this loading error. Caps were found loose. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Quick Dry was used to determine the extent of leakage. Drying sand did not soak anything up but green discoloration was found on the flap in which the hazmat damages were found indicating past leakage. PH indicator was used to confirm that it was dry prior to continuing to unload the remaining packages from this trailer. No color was indicated which meant it had already dried.

SequenceEvent: Recovered from trailer on unload. Upon recovery, package was found around other hazmat damages. Heavy external leakage was found on the outside of the package meaning PH testing was necessary. Upon testing, area was found to have dried into the flap it which it and others were found. DescribePack: Caps were found to be loose with heavy internal and external leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Quick Dry was used to soak up any potential spill. PH testing powder was used to determine if any spillage was not yet neutralized. No color showed up following this meaning it was neutralized already.

SequenceEvent: package was brought to qa table wet. package was placed in haz drum immediately DescribePack: side bod box was wet. top of container cap wet. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: bagged and placed in drum

SequenceEvent: Wet package identified during sort and moved to QA for inspection DescribePack: Inner plastic bottle leaked from threaded cap, outer box damaged by liquid DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Damaged package segregated in plastic lined drum. Nearby packages and surfaces inspected for spillage.

SequenceEvent: Hazmat was unloaded off trailer. Package handler then ignored the orientation arrows, turned it on its side and slid it underneath rollers. It then ate through the seal and cap causing the liquid to leak out. DescribePack: The seal and cap due to the interior of the liquid DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PH Neutralizer to eliminate the effects

SequenceEvent: Box discovered wet and leaking but not otherwise damaged. DescribePack: plastic cap not screwed on properly, misaligned. approximately 0.5 gallons leaked DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: box placed in plastic tote under ventilator hood in hazmat cage

SequenceEvent: UPON INITIAL INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE WAS WET AND SLIGHTLYCORRODED. AFTER LOOKING INSIDE THE BOTTLES HAD LOOSE CAPS AND MISSING SOME LIQUID CONTENTS DescribePack: LOOSE BOTTLE CAPS DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PLACED IN PLASTIC BAG INSIDE TOTE

SequenceEvent: THE SEQUENCE IS UNKNOWN. DescribePack: THIS PKG CONTAINS FOUR ONE GALLON JUGS OF LIQUID CLEANING SOLUTION. UNFORTUNATELY, THIS PACKAGE BECAME DAMAGED WHILE IN TRANSIT. ONE OF THE CONTAINERS HAS A CRACK IN ITS UPPER BODY. AS A RESULT, SOME OF THE LIQUID HAS LEAKED OUT OF THE CONTAINER. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Took off truck and isolated from package handlers. Reclosed box and check truck for any damage packages.

SequenceEvent: The package had gotten nocked over, but was not damaged. When the package was on its side the contents of 1 of the bottles began to leak out. DescribePack: 1 bottle had a loose cap. There was no seal under the cap. The content was leaking out from under the cap and them leaking out fo the box. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed into a plastic tote.

SequenceEvent: package was brought to QA from the unload. The package was wet when I opened the package it had four bottles of Ethyl Acetate two of which was leaking due to loose caps. DescribePack: loose caps DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: hazmat was put in a bag and hazmat container

DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A TOTE LINED WITH A HAZMAT BAG.

SequenceEvent: During transit the caps became loose, when discovered QA was called. Spill pads were used to clean up spilled product. Soiled clean up equipment and package were placed in a lined red tote. SequenceEvent: Package was being unloaded and was mishandled, resulting in first spillage. Package was put inside of hazmat tote on its side instead of right side up, causing it to leak further from top of container. Package was given to QA for damage-processing. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was put inside of hazmat tote and given to QA.

SequenceEvent: BOX WAS BAGGED AND LEFT IN THE HWPA IN A RED TOTE. DescribePack: THE BOX WAS BAGGED SEPERATELY FROM THE BOTTLES. CAPS SCREWED. LIQUID AT THE VENT HOLES. TOP HALF OF THE BOX SATURATED. column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE LVD PICK-OFF ON THE PD-3. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE TURNED OFF AND SECURED THE CONVEYOR BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 4 MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GALLON JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/2 ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 10 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE SIDES   BOTTOM OF THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS/INCH EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column168: THE HAZ-MAT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING ON THE FLOOR OF THE UNLOAD DOCK E IN THE UPS EARTH CITY, MO HUB. AT 20:00 THE PACKAGE (A 12X12X12 INCH 275LBS BURSTING TEST DOUBLE WALL FIBERBOARD BOX) WAS FOUND ON ITS SIDE ON THE FLOOR WET AND DISCOLORED FROM THE SPILLAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP CAGE FOR PROCESSING. AN EXTERNAL INSPECTION SHOWED NO SIGNS OF ABUSE FROM THE SHIPPING PROCESS. THE INTERNAL INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS ENOUGH PACKING MATERIAL TO PROTECT THE INNER RECEPTACLES (1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES) FROM THE SHIPPING PROCESS. THE SPILLAGE WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A COMBINATION OF A LOOSE CAP AND THE PACKAGE BEING ON ITS SIDE. ALL MATERIAL HAS BEEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.

During an inbound inspection of tank car TILX 112330 (Loaded, Hydrochloric Acid, UN 1789, Class 8, PG II) at the CN Kirk Yard in Gary, IN., a CN mechanical employee observed a green liquid dripping down the side of the tank car from the top side. All appropriated departments were notified. A CN Dangerous Goods Officer's inspection of the tank car revealed a small leak emanating from the liquid line top blind flange assembly. The intact security seal # RCR 221994 was removed from the protective housing to perform the inspection. The inspection revealed (1) of the (4) Liquid eduction line securement flange fasteners was corroded/degraded impeding its ability to be properly tightened to form a secure seal allowing the product to leak in transportation. The CN DGO replaced the damaged all thread securement bolt and nuts with like kind and tightened until the leak was stopped. The car has been placed in hold at the CN Kirk Yard pending exterior decontamination and proper repairs by the car owner

SequenceEvent: Unsure specifics of event, appears that package was damaged during transit inside trailer, package was isolated when identified as hazardous and taken out of sortation DescribePack: Box appeared to contain 4 total bottles of industrial cleaner, only 3 bottles were found, 1 of the bottle's cap was loose which caused leakage, missing 1 5L container of cleaner DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: package was removed from sortation and placed in designated area for clean up

SequenceEvent: When we began unloading the belly, there was a liquid substance covering the bottom of the entire trailer. Someone said that it was hair dye and that they found the box, so I thought nothing of it. In the last few feet of the trailer, a bucket was discovered with the lid partially off and completely empty. Upon inspection, I realized it was a hazmat, whereupon I cleared the area and informed QA, checking the SDS and ensuring that any of the package handlers working on that truck washed their hands well. By my estimate, ~35 packages were affected, possibly more, most likely requiring extensive repacks. DescribePack: the bucket has a dent in the rim and the lid most of the lid came off the bucket DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: QA cleared the area of all activity then began to place exorbitant pads on the bed of the trailer to exurb majority of the liquid then placing the soiled boxes and pads in to a hazmat disposable bags, then QA cleaned up the remaining liquid.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO QA AFTER BEING UNLOADED ON 5/17. IT WAS NOT IN A BOX WITH HAZMAT LABELING SO AFTRE INVESTIGATING AND SEEING IT WAS A HAZMAT IT WAS PLACED IN A YELLO DRUM AND SECURED. DPR WAS ENTERED AND FURTHER INSPECTION. BECUASE THE PKG SAT OVER THE WEEKEND I ASSUME IT LEAKED SLOWLY THAT WHOLE TIME. LUCKLY THE CAPS WERE ONLY SLIGHTLY LOOSE AND MINIMAL DAMAGE WAS DONE TO THIS BOX ONLY. DescribePack: PKG LOOKED TO BE REPACKED EITHER FROM THE ORIGIN FACILITY OR SPAR-293 WHILE IN TRANSIT. THE BAG INSIDE WAS A CLEAR HAZMAT BAG THAT STATIONS USE AND THE BOX WAS NOT THE ORIGINAL BOX AS SEEN IN SPIDR IMAGES. THE INNER PACKING WAS RATHER POOR. THE BAG INSIDE WAS NOT ZIP TIED OR TIED SHUT IN ANY WAY, BOTTLES WERE NOT PACKED IN THE PROPER SIZE BOX CAUSE THEY WERE ON THEIR SIDES WHEN THEY ARRIVED, AND NO OUTTER LABEL CODES WERE APPLIED TO THE BOX. THE CAPS MUST HAVE BEEN LOOSE WHEN THEY LEFT THE ORIGIN FACILITY CAUSE YOU CAN SEE IN SPIDR IMAGES THAT A CORNER OF THE PACKAGE IS ALREADY WET IN THE IMAGES. NO HOLES OR CRACKS IN ANY OF THE GALLON JUGS. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE WAS OPENED IMMEDIATELY AND BOTTLES WERE PLACED UPRIGHT AND LIDS WERE TIGHTENED. EVERYTHING WAS PLACED IN A NEW HAZMAT BAG AND PUT IN A YELLOW HAZMAT DRUM. NO OTHER PAKCAKGES WERE DAMAGED.

column168: SUPERVISOR RADIOED LEAKING PACKAGE

Upon arrival at the delivery destination, a drum of material was discovered to be compromised on the trailer at the top of the drum where the drum chime meets the drum body. The drum was not leaking when sitting still and had shown evidence of leaking approximately 1 ounce of liquid during transit. A hazardous material contractor was called to the scene to wipe down the liquid on the side of the drum and place the drum into an overpack container so it could safely be returned to the destination terminal for disposition. Due to the hazard of material, the package specifications could not be safely obtained. Investigation revealed that the drum had likely been punctured by the tip of a forklift blade at some point during the unloading process.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had the forklift operator used more precaution when down stacking freight from the top of the drums. This incident has already been used in dock safety topics to illustrate the importance of proper freight handling procedures while operating the forklift.

column168: SequenceEvent: When a package handler went to load this package to a van, they noticed that it was damp and smelled of gasoline.  This package was then removed from the package flow and brought to QA. Upon inspection, it proved to contain 4 1-gallon jugs of 50:1 2-cycle fuel. DescribePack: The plastic outer cap of one of the jugs was detached.  The metal inner cap of the that jug was loose.  Some small amount of its contents had leaked out. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was immediately placed into a lined hazmat tote.  There was now apparent leakage beyond the package itself.

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY AN UNLOADER IN UNLOAD-E. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED AND A 2 FOOT RADIUS PUDDLE RESULTING FROM THE SPILL CLEANED UP. THEN ALL DAMAGED   CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE CONSOLIDATED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1 GALLON JUGS HAD POPPED COMPLETELY OFF OF THE RECEPTACLE, CAUSING MOST OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE BASE OF THE CARTON, AS WELL AS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column168: CN DGO was contacted by CN Mechanical supervisor about tank car PROX 42073 (Load / UN 3082 / Class 9 / PG III ) that was rejected from Minnesota Commercial Railroad in New Brighton, MN. The railcar had product on the sides of the car that appeared to be coming from the manway cover. The railcar was isolated.  All required notifications were made.  CN Response team responded and also observed the railcar with product on the sides.  Upon closer inspection, a shipper seal was found intact on the manway cover lid.  The manway bolts were checked for tool tightness and 2 were found to be loose.   The manway bolts were properly tightened which secured the leak.  The exterior of the railcar was cleaned of all product residue. The railcar was released onto destination.

column168: I RESPONDED TO THE PACKAGE AT DOOR 188. FOUND THE LEAKING PACKAGE, WHICH WAS LABELLED AS A CLASS 5.1 (8) HAZMAT (HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS), ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH A WET SIDE. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED A 5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER WHICH WAS LEAKING FROM THE LID. THE PACKAGE WAS RETURNED TO THE PSC FOR PROCESSING AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP AS A LIQUID (OXIDIZER).

AT ABOUT 1145 AM PSC GOT A CALL FOR A LEAKING HAZMAT NEAR REVENUE RECOVERY, UPON RECEIVING THE CALL I FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PPE. THE PACKAGE HAD ONE MARK ON THE CORNER OF THE BOX. I THEN BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO THE PSC FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

UPON OPENING TRAILER DOOR, SUPERVISOR VISUALLY IDENTIFIED LEAKING PACKAGE, REPORTED EVENT TO RESPONDER, REPORTED SEEING CORROSIVE 8 LABEL IN ADDITION. RESPONDER VISUALLY CONFIRMED SUPERVISOR OBSERVATIONS, INCLUDING A COLLAPSED FINAL WALL WHICH DISPLACED BOX FAR FROM ORIGINAL POSITION. RESPONDER CLEANED SPILL AND AFFECTED PACKAGES TO PSC FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column168: Veolia employees were preparing a shipment for transport.  10 x 55 gallon metal drums of organic solvent solution were loaded into the box van utilizing a drum dolly from the shipper's site. The Veolia employees were moving the drums around in order to secure the load when they noticed a wet spot where a drum was sitting. After the employees examined the drum they noticed a small leak originated from the bottom chime which resulting in a small leak, approximately <10 mL. There was no evidence of any spill where the drum was stored nor during the loading process.  The drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum.   Do to the nature of this spill, Veolia believes that it was due to manufacturer's defect which had a compromised chime.  There was no evidence of the chime being bent or warp utilizing the drum dolly and inspecting the dolly did not show any sharp edges that would have damaged the chime.
column169: After thorough review, Veolia believes that it took all necessary precautions and was able to minimize the potential for a greater spill by catching the leak prior to it going out on the road.  Veolia will continue to train its employees on examining the integrity of the drums prior to shipment.

The waste was then transported to the XPO terminal located in Romulus, MI for terminal personnel to manage.

column43: Sulfuric Acid with water and a certain amount of lead (electric storage)
column168: A small skid of batteries were loaded in the nose of the cargo area in the back of an enclosed straight (box) truck. The batteries were picked up by a company driver with the intention of transporting them back to the company warehouse. The (core) batteries are owned by the transporting company, as the company stores are serviced by the company warehouse on a daily/weekly basis.    The pallet of batteries were placed on a wooden pallet and shrink wrapped to provide stability and securement. One of the batteries was placed on the outer edge of the pallet with the side-mounted terminals facing outward. The pallet of batteries was placed on the truck against the metal sheeting that encompasses the lower internal wall of the cargo area.     During transport, the side mounted battery terminals made contact with the metal wall sheeting which caused the battery to produce an amount of heat sufficient to damage the packaging and wooden pallet. The driver noticed the evolution of heat when he stopped at his next servicing store location. The driver extinguished the battery fire with the truck fire extinguisher.    The package failure was caused by commodity self-ignition and improper preparation for transportation. There was a minimum release and the duration is undeterminable.
column169: The incident has been reviewed and the following Corrective Actions have been implemented:   1, A company email was sent to the Warehouse GM's and transportation managers to verify that the CMV 's are equipped with the proper fire extinguisher(s) per FMCSR 49 CFR 393.95.   2. A company email was sent to the Warehouse GM's and CMV Drivers which included an internal training documents titled "One Point Safety Lesson - Incident Alert - Battery Fire." A signed acknowledgment was requested upon review.    3. A company email was sent to the Store Managers and Regional Managers which included the internal training documents titled "One Point Safety Lesson - Incident Alert - Battery Fire."   CMV Drivers and Warehouse Hazmat employees are assigned Hazmat General Awareness, Safety and Security Training. There are also job specific training(s) for core battery, cargo securement, and hazmat driver transportation.

One of the batteries was placed on the outer edge of the pallet with the side-mounted terminals facing outward. The pallet of batteries was placed on the truck against the metal sheeting that encompasses the lower internal wall of the cargo area.     During transport, the side mounted battery terminals made contact with the metal wall sheeting which caused the battery to produce an amount of heat sufficient to damage the packaging and wooden pallet. The driver noticed the evolution of heat when he stopped at his next servicing store location. The driver extinguished the battery fire with the truck fire extinguisher.    The package failure was caused by commodity self-ignition and improper preparation for transportation. There was a minimum release and the duration is undeterminable.
column169: The incident has been reviewed and the following Corrective Actions have been implemented:   1, A company email was sent to the Warehouse GM's and transportation managers to verify that the CMV 's are equipped with the proper fire extinguisher(s) per FMCSR 49 CFR 393.95.   2. A company email was sent to the Warehouse GM's and CMV Drivers which included an internal training documents titled "One Point Safety Lesson - Incident Alert - Battery Fire." A signed acknowledgment was requested upon review.    3. A company email was sent to the Store Managers and Regional Managers which included the internal training documents titled "One Point Safety Lesson - Incident Alert - Battery Fire."   CMV Drivers and Warehouse Hazmat employees are assigned Hazmat General Awareness, Safety and Security Training. There are also job specific training(s) for core battery, cargo securement, and hazmat driver transportation.

column168: Around 0630 central time, a company tractor pulling a DOT 407 tanker was offloading product into a bin at the Austin Powder facility in Pinkerton, TN.  The driver was midway through pumping the product off, and went into the cab of the vehicle to complete paperwork.  When he returned a few moments later, the burst disc had blown sending about 2800# of product onto the parking lot, which was hard packed gravel.  The burst disc functioned as it should, so no packaging failure.    The driver immediately stopped the flow of product.  The parking lot is flat, and weather conditions were dry, so no product ran off the lot, and was confined to a circle about 15 foot in diameter under the trailer.  The driver called into his dispatcher, as well as to Chemtrec.  Austin contacted a spill crew to come out and clean up the product.  The product was containerized along with impacted gravel, and taken to an Austin facility.
column169: The driver was given time off without pay, and has undergone retraining in the area of offloading product, specifically staying in attendance of the process.  Since there was no "packaging failure", we can only look at the burst discs  we are using, and make sure that they are not defective.  It is worth noting that when offloading the remainder of the product (after the spill), an additional burst disc blew.  This is being looked into as a possible causative  item in this spill.  That said, we are primarily viewing this as a training and driver behavior issue, and because of that will be covering this with our driver group making similar deliveries.

column168: On May 04, 2022,  ERTS was notified of a load shift that occurred on trailer# 667305. The Driver of Truck# 575210 reported that he made a hard stop causing one of the poly drums containing UN2922 Catacarb 922 to release an estimated 30-gallons of product to the trailer floor and to an underlying asphalt area. No drains or waterway were impacted.  The Cleaning Guys supervisor arrived onsite first and stated absorbents were placed on the roadway and the spill was contained. Once the rest of the crew arrived onsite the trailer was offloaded to clean the impacted area on the trailer floor. The Cleaning Guys advised that a single 55-gallon poly drum ruptured when it impacted the trailer floor as the result of a load shift. Based on the liquid contents still contained in the damaged drum, it was estimated that up to 30-gallons of product was spilled. The damaged drum was subsequently placed into poly overpack drum for continued transit with Landstar to the intended location. Following visual assessment, absorbent was spread over the impacted area on the roadway. All drums were wiped and neutralized before being loaded back on the trailer. Cleaning Guys had to grind floor dry over the trailer floor to remove residual product. Following neutralization activities, pH test paper strips were used to field screen the trailer floor and underlying asphalt. The associated pH screening indicated a neutral PH. Prior to contractor departure, absorbents and debris were swept into a single 55-gallon drum, which is currently pending disposal.

column168: On May 06, 2022, Landstar notified ERTS of a truck on fire carrying hazardous packages in the trailer. The fire originally combusted in the tractor for unknown reasons. The Fire Department arrived on site and was able to extinguish the fire. EnviroServe arrived onsite and reported the truck and trailer were both burned badly. EnviroServe unloaded the trailer and (16) 275-gallon totes of "CSI-2255", of which 6 of them lost all 275-gallons in each.  The other 10 did not have any spill but they were blistered and melted from the fire. All of the products in the 10 totes are contaminated by melted plastic and were heated up by the fire as well so they were not salvageable. EnviroServe pumped out the totes with a vac truck into new totes. A 100' by 40' area was secured for future excavation. The impacted soil area was secured by creating dirt berms to contain the soil area. No poly was used due to the large area and the risk for the poly to come loose. A 13' by 100' area of asphalt under the trailer was impacted.  On June 02, 2022, EnviroServe arrived onsite to begin the excavation, 50 x 40-foot area was excavated to a depth of approximately 2-inches below the original grade. Excavated material was directly loaded into a single roll-off container, which will be transported for disposal.  30 yards of soil was excavated and containerized into a total of three (3) roll-off containers. On June 06, 2022, EnviroServe returned to the site to finish the remediation, A total of 5 roll-off containers were filled at this time.  Future excavation is scheduled for June 08, 2022.

column168: When the driver arrived at the railyard product was leaking out from the dome lid area.  On inspection they found that it was missing a dome gasket.  The trailer was prepped at the tankwash and it calls for a specific gasket to be installed which the tankwash did install.  However that special gasket is designed for our over the road trailers, not our intermodal containers that take a different size gasket.  When the dome lid was closed and sealed either at the tankwash or the shipper facility the gasket fell down inside the trailer.  The product that did leak out evaporated quickly.
column169: We worked with the tankwash to ensure they know to only use the correct size dome gaskets for our intermodal containers.  A different prep was created on our end to reflect this more clearly.  This should be an isolated incident.

column168: At 0904 ET, XPO terminal XPK reported a release of 3-4 liters of STEAMATE PAS8040 from a 237-liter tote due to unknown causes in Williamstown, WV. The release was contained to the trailer and did not affect any storm drains or waterways. ERTS dispatched Zema Brothers to conduct cleanup. At 1741 ET, crew arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1.5 gallons of product released to a 4' x 4' area of the trailer floor. Crew advised the Camlock cap popped off as a result of built up pressure inside the tote. After inspection, the tote was found to not be leaking, however once the cap popped off, neighboring freight was impacted. 42 boxes of food grade "Nestle Boost" were impacted and drummed up as waste. The boxes were placed into an 85 gallon metal, 55 gallon poly, and a 35 gallon poly drums. Absorbents were worked into the impacted trailer floor as well which was placed into a 20 gallon and 10 gallon metal drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XCH reported 13-gallons of UN2014 "Option Liquid Non Chlorine" released into the trailer and onto the dock floor from a 15-gallon poly drum that was punctured by a forklift. ERTS dispatched HEPACO to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 2045 ET HEPACO personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 15-gallons of product released to a 80' x30' and a 80' x 1' area of the dock floor and concrete yard.  HEPACO placed the original 15-gallon poly drum into a 55-gallon poly drum with acid gator and also generated another 55-gallon poly drum with just acid gator. The 55-gallon poly drum containing the original 15-gallon drum began to build pressure and heat once the lid was secured, HEPACO personnel then added more acid gator to the original drum. Water was also added to each drum to delude the waste product and more absorbents were added to the liquid. The 55-gallon drum containing the 15-gallon poly drum and absorbents was overpacked into a 95-gallon drum because it contained more absorbents. column168: 1029 ET, XPO Logistics (USL) contacted ERTS to report a regulated cargo release. It was reported a 330 gallon plastic tote containing Sulfuric Acid 36% was discovered leaking due to unknown reasons, releasing a total of 1 cup of the product to the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched Patriot Environmental to conduct cleanup. At 1632 ET, Patriot personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3 cups of product released to the top of the tote from a crack. The product was transferred out of the damaged tote into a new tote and 2 closed top drums. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris waste into a 55 gallon poly drum.

XPO Logistics UOR reported a release of Hexafluoro-2-propanol from a 4 gallon box due to damage. ERTS dispatched Patriot for cleanup. At 2230 ET, Patriot personnel arrived onsite. They confirmed terminal personal had emptied the trailer and cleaned the release with oil dri. The absorbents and box were placed into a poly trash can. Patriot transferred the waste into a 55 gallon poly drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 1308 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (XCN) about a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift puncture, an unknown amount of Sodium Bisulfite Solution 40%(Hazardous - UN2693) released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor and the "B" yard.  ERTS dispatched Hepaco for cleanup. At 1420 ET, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2 gallons of product released to a 5' x 5' area of the trailer floor. The remaining product from the damaged tote was transferred into a new tote for salvage with the original placard labels. The damaged tote bladder and impacted absorbents were containerized into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. Waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On 5/29/2022, a crew working in the CSX Acca Yard, in Richmond, Virginia, reported an odor emanating from UTLX 663857- a loaded tank car of Cyclohexanone. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a faint odor in the area with no apparent source of release from the car.  Additionally, Joseph McCann, CSX’s Sr. Manager of Hazardous Materials, responded to the incident along with HEPACO on the morning of May 30.  Upon further inspection of the car it was determined that the car had a non-accident release (NAR) of product vapor from the manway cover due to improperly secured manway cover bolts. Contractor and CSX personnel opened the manway cover, inspected the cover gasket, and secured the cover for transportation.  Additionally, response crew members applied thread lubricant to the manway cover bolts to ensure adequate sealing force of the manway cover.

column168: Empire Express retained ERTS of a cargo incident in Sparta, KY. The incident began when the trailer brakes caught fire, and the driver pulled over to attempt to put the fire out but was unable to, causing the fire to spread inside the trailer. The police department arrived on the scene to assist, and the fire department arrived as well. No shipping manifest or BOL was available as the police took it when they arrived, but it was stated the cargo consisted of UN3260 (19 supersacks - IBC ) . The trailer and the tractor were separated by the driver and there was no release from the tractor. Hepaco Environmental responded for clean up operations and advised that all 19 IBCs released impacted the asphalt roadway, adjacent soil and migrated to the Eagle Creek. Hepaco personnel utilized hand tools and heavy equipment to clean the impacted areas. All waste was collected for pending disposal. Weekly site monitoring was conducted and no added impact to the Eagle creek was observed. The soil sites are pending final restoration operations at this time and will be coordinated with State and local authorities.

column168: During off loading it was discovered that the load had shifted and that one of the 330 gallon tote of Sodium Hydroxide (un1824) had been punctured by a sharp object and had released 175 gallons of product.  Contractors were dispatched for the containment and cleanup of the release.

The container was picked up at the shipper's location in Sterling, VA on 5/19/22. At the time, it was not leaking. When the material was off-loaded at it's final destination for treatment and storage in York, PA on 5/20/22, some material had leaked out onto the floor of the trailer. It was not a lot of material, no more than 2 quarts, and it did not escape the trailer. The container was also no longer leaking, indicating that that there was likely only one or two of the inner containers had leaked. The package was loaded onto a pallet and the leak was from the bottom, from abrasion against the pallet. The spill inside the trailer was cleaned up in-house.
column169: The package has recently been approved for a special permit (SP-21334) which authorizes it for this material, but limits the package weight to 452lbs and the use of absorbent for inner containers of liquid to prevent leakage from the container. We have reviewed the requirements of the special permit with the shipper.

column168: On 05/25/2022 LARS received notification from Hub personnel that unit JBHU 320039 was observed leaking after the unit was deramped from the railcar at the San Bernardino Intermodal Facility. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed inside of the containment pit pending a cargo inspection. Environmental contractor (United Pumping) was dispatched to perform a cargo inspection and to remediate the leaking product along with the affected areas. Interior inspection revealed floor loaded 55 gallon drums of HAZ Aroset PS 6384 Adhesive throughout the container. 1 drum was found to be punctured and leaking in the middle of the unit, the substance leaking did leak to the exterior of the unit with approximately 12oz reaching the ground. Blocking and bracing was applied at the rear of this shipment. Contractor was able to remediate the spill and affected areas, the spilled product was identified as Aroset PS 6384 Adhesive. The shipment was reloaded / secured with seal 27670375
column169: Ensure load is secured against movement anticipated during rail shipment to prevent damage to containers.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: The PROX 17426 was found by BNSF employees to be leaking a small amount from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and responders identified a small leak of sulfuric acid from the liquid line cap.  The cap was found to be less than tool tight.  Less than 1 KG of Sulfuric Acid was released from the car and isolated to the car body only, no environmental impacts.  Sodium Bicarb was used to neutralize the acid on the car, the car was depressurized to inspect the cap and gasket.  Once cleaned, the car was secured and released back into transportation.
column169: The shipper should review post loading procedures to ensure that all appliances and fittings are properly tool tightened for transportation.

column168: At 11:50 am on May 19, it was observed that the top portion of a poly tote in a truck that had been recently backed in to our dock was cracked.  Approximately 15 gallons of liquid acid rinsate had spilled onto the truck/van floor, a portion of which also passed through the truck/van floor onto the pavement.  Clean-up was performed by our 40-hour hazwoper trained team, and the materials remaining in the damaged tote were transferred to another tote.
column169: The shipper was notified that the tote had failed, and was requested to use totes without degraded/aged materials

column168: Univar Solutions was delivering sulfuric acid to our customer. After filling out the proper paperwork and starting the chemical transfer there was an overflow of the customer's storage tank. The overflow was due to the customer's telemetery system not functioning properly.  The tank capacity is 6000 gallons and the overflow occurred when the customer's tank was showing 4980 gallons on their telemetry system.  Customer ordered 3600 gallons and Univar Solution's truck was delivering 3556 gallons.   Customer advised they cleaned up and used the spilled residue in the wastewater treatment system. No injuries occurred, no agencies contacted.

column168: On May 23, 2022 at approximately 11:00 New Jersey State DOT Inspector Alan Fisher reported that NATX 310314 was leaking vapor from the vacuum relief at the Port Reading Yard. NATX 310314 was a loaded tank car of UN 1268, Petroleum Distillates (hexane).  Conrail Manager of Hazardous Material, Joe Caccamo and Marion Environmental responded to inspect the tank car. It was found that the vacuum relief device was indeed faulty and it was removed and replaced with a blind flange. One Time Movement Approval was obtained to continue to destination and then to home shop for repairs. No further action on Conrail is required.  the faulty VRV was sent to:  ATTN: Tommy Summers McKenzie Valve & Machining LLC 145 Airport Road McKenzie, TN 38201  cause code 1057  NARRI 2 (5+5+0) X (2+ 0)  =40

column168: On May 27, 2022, Landstar notified ERTS of a release of Heptanes inside Trailer 698742 following a “braking” incident that caused a load shift. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to confirm amount released and perform clean up. Following contractor arrival and visual assessment, it was determined that an 8’ by 8’ area of the trailer floor was impacted by spillage from (3) 5-gallon buckets of product that were damaged as the result of this cargo shift. Leaking cargo was containerized into a single 55-gallon drum along with absorbents utilized to address affected trailer floor components.

SequenceEvent: Package was found damaged in the unload, with one side of the box being completely destroyed due to the acid. Package was at first treated as a normal damaged package, since there were not any DOT Labels/markings, nor was there a FedEx Hazmat label (there was only a normal FedEx barcode label). Upon further inspection, the package contained a SDS for the inner contents which showcased and/confirmed that the contents were hazardous. DescribePack: One side of the package was disintegrated due to the acid. One of the two inner bottles had a loose cap which resulted in the leakage. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Upon inspection and confirmation of the hazardous nature of the contents, the package was immediately relocated to the hazmat cage, away from all non-essential personnel.

on May 29, 2022, Landstar contacted ERTS requesting service related to a 1.5 gallon release of UN 1866 "Nutack 046-466" from a 55 gallon DM. ERTS dispatched a remediation contactor Lonestar to address the reported spill. Following contractor arrival and cargo assessment, it was determined that 1 gallon of product affected an 8’ by 1’ area of trailer flooring and a 1’ x 1’ underlying asphalt area. The leak was observed to be from the bottom of the drum, near the weld seam, where it appeared the drum had been dragged on the ground, which resulted in a “scrape” pattern at the immediate vicinity of the leak. Media affected was subsequently addressed by the contractor and waste generated is currently pending disposal.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: On May 6 a Tradebe Transportation LLC driver made a customer pickup in Milwaukee, Wl. The drums were loaded by forklift by the, customer on the tail end of the trailer and the Tradebe Transportation LLC driver used a drum dolly to move the drums into his trailer. After loading the drums and leaving the customer's location the driver was flagged by a motorist saying they saw some material dripping from his trailer.. The driver stopped in a safe location and id6ntified two drums that were leaking; he opened his spill kit and used oil dry and booms to soak up the material and put the leaking drums overpacks. It was determined that after the drums were loaded that the drum dolly was unsecured in the back of the trailer and damaged the drums by puncturing them.
column169: After loading drums or any types of packages into the trailer for transport, it is necessary to secure any material handling equipment: drum dolly, pallet jack during before the vehicle leaves the customer's location for transport; always make sure the vehicle has additional straps to tie down material handling equipment.

column14: US NNA DO SANDIA NATIONAL LAB
column168: In 2021, our customer(Sandia National Laboratory, SNL) subcontracted Excelitas to return inert scrap(i.e. not containing energetic material) hardware that had accumulated at our Miamisburg, OH facility for over 20+ years of production. The hardware was reviewed by Excelitas and SNL personnel and determined to be material needing to be returned to SNL. The hardware was packaged and shipped to SNL in a corrugated box within a metal AN can. The shipment was offered by Excelitas- Miamisburg on August 17,2021 and consisted of 6. packages- 4 AN cans with scrap material, 1 AN can with packing material, and 1 box with packing material. Transportation was by FedEx. The shipment was delivered to SNL- New Mexico on August 18, 2021. The shipment arrived at SNL- Building 905 around August 25, 2021. The shipment was sent to Building 905 for sorting by the responsible product realization teams(PRTs) in the explosive receipt and inspection area of the facility. PRTs claimed items with continued Value to their programs, with the unclaimed items getting sent to Repplication. This occurred in September 2021. In April 2022, the(part specific) PRT retrieved the"previously" functioned/fired LAT units for potential use in production of trainers, to include the unit in question. While sorting through the units, an SNL technologist identified a single(part specific) actuator that had not fired and was a LIVE unit(containing energetic material). Excelitas was notified on May 4,2022. Research into the history of the unit(SN71357) showed item was from(part specific) Lot 2 (circa December 2011) and had been used in the Neyer Fire Test regime. The records indicate this unit did not fire during testing. The unit contains less than 0.100 grams of TiH1.65KCIO4(non-static sensitive, pyrotechnic).
column169: Both Sandia National Laboratory and Excelitas- Miamisburg have initiated investigation/root-cause, correction actions(RCCA). Initial results of the investigation at Excelitas- Miamisburg prove to be difficult to account for the identification of the RCCA because of the time Iapse from production/testing of the part(i.e. 2011) to the return shipment to SNL in August 2021. However, the RCCA continues with a multi-functional team with Miamisburg Senior Leadership Team oversight. Excelitas Corporate Leadership is updated with periodical briefings. Initial suggestions for corrective actions include, in no particular order: 1. Sitewide training on proper segregation of LIVE and INERT parts 2. Functional(i.e. destructive testing) specific training of operational controls 3. Procedure reviews for(part specific) 4. Development of general post-LAT disposition procedure 5. Procedure review of QP0759(Scrap Disposal) to account for off-specification disposal 6. Existing and future SNL contracts have direction on the return of production parts

column168: On 5/25/2022 at 9:40 AM, Kansas City Southern Railway's(KCS) Manager Shop Operations at the Shreveport, LA rail yard notified the KCS Environmental& Hazmat Department that hazmat car UTLX 685147 was leaking from the top of the car. A railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to Investigate and mitigate the leak. Upon arrival, the contractor determined that the liquid valve was In the full open position and the secondary closure plug was not Installed. Estimated release was 10 gallons. The liquid valve was fully closed and the secondary closure plug installed tool tight. The contractor verified that all other closures were secured and the outside of UTLX 685147 was wiped down before the contractor departed the yard. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a 'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package Is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.

column168: NexTier CNG Logistics Driver was Delivering CNG transport T1020 from Pecos Power Solutions to location. At 7:59 P.M. the NexTier driver was traveling North on highway 285 attempting to turn East onto highway 302 at 14 MPH. While exiting the intersection of highway 285 and 302 that is under construction the driver was making a righthand turn getting onto highway 302. Due to the road construction, there is a steep approach transitioning onto highway 302.  When the driver crested the incline the right passenger trailer duals went over first causing the load to shift left then the drivers left duals went over causing the load to shift right. Due to the high center of gravity and liquid the movement it caused load to slingshot back to the left with enough momentum to overturn tractor TR185 and Trailer T1020.  During the motor vehicle accident one of the CNG bottles on the trailer was damaged and a release of CNG occurred. The bladder system was isolated and approximately 10,300 MSCF of CNG was released. There was no ignition.
column169: Intersection of the accident was closed down for use internally by NexTier Senior Management. All commercial motor vehicle traffic is banned from utilizing this area of roadway until construction is completed.  Central Dispatch will monitor all state road construction web sites to avoid commercial motor vehicles from traveling in active construction zones across all company locations.

column168: Description: Operator was in the process of loading the last load from railcar MDCX1175 into trailer 8120. Driver had given him the signal that the trailer was half full. In preparation, operator shut down the compressor air and returned to railcar. He then was going to switch the airline but failed to ensure the air valve was closed. When he removed the airline, product travelled from the product hose connection back into the airline which started to spray acid which sprayed onto the operator. Operator was sent to hospital in Tucson for treatment. Invetigative Findings: Operator failed to close the air valve on the product hose before removing the hose. Operator did not have the required PPE as stated in the SOP(No Acid Suit Jacket, No Respirator, No Acid Hood, Using dark face shield at night and in up position). Operator did not rinse for 15 minutes after being sprayed as outlined in the SOP based on an estimated timeline. Operator left the loading process unattended to scale out previous truck which is violation of the SOP. Driver was refusing treatment, Safety Coordinator instructed operator to seek medical attention and was transported by the driver. Root Cause: Operator failed to follow several steps in the SOP. Main cause is valve was not properly secured.
column169: CTI had a Safety Stand Down with employees at site to cover incident,'discuss procedures, suggest ways to improve process to eliminate any additional risk, importance of teamwork with everyone involved with the process and to slow down and don't rush. CTI will revise the SOP to incorporate a NOTE stating both Driver and Transload Operator will stand down and not perform the transload operation if one of them are not compliance with their PPE requirements. CTI will issue the revised SOP to all drivers and loaders, as well as conduct a safety meeting with employees affected by this change cn will increase random, unannounced safety observation from the Safety Team, as well as the managers responsible for the area. CTI will emphasize the procedures to all affected personnel that if acid makes contact with the skin the shower or eyewash station rinse should be 15 minutes as outlined in SOP CTI will have a Transload Operator Working Meeting to discuss safety and procedures. The SOP will be reviewed by the Transload Operators from all CTI sites during this meeting.
